<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910425-0059</DOCNO><DOCID>910425-0059.</DOCID><HL>   Ex-Head of Stock Firm   Pleads Guilty in Trades   Of Stolen Certificates</HL><DATE>04/25/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C18</SO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>SECURITIES REGULATIONS AND ENFORCEMENT (RGU)SECURITIES (SCR)</IN><NS>SECURITIES REGULATION (RGU)</NS><LP>   NEW YORK -- The former president of a now-defunct New Yorkbrokerage firm pleaded guilty to charges of trading $50,000in stolen stock certificates.   Manhattan District Attorney Robert Morgenthau said RichardSchwartz, former president of Richardson, Lyle and Adler,admitted that he opened an account at the firm in the name ofMary Kleve by forging various documents, and knowinglydeposited the stolen certificates into the account. Thecertificates were then sold, with the proceeds transferred toa bank account through a series of unauthorized transactions.</LP><TEXT>   The certificates were stolen from the home of Ms. Kleve,an executive with Estee Lauder who died in a June 1989 planecrash, shortly after her death. The district attorney saidthe investigation into the theft is continuing.   Mr. Schwartz pleaded guilty to a violation of the MartinAct which prohibits a broker from trading stolen securities.He faces up to four years in prison when sentenced on June 5.   Mr. Schwartz couldn't be reached for comment, and hisattorney declined to comment on the matter.</TEXT></DOC>